SIMPLE: overwork
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overwork
<hw>O`ver*work"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Overworked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or
<conjf>Overwrought</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Overworking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To work beyond
the strength; to cause to labor too much or too long; to tire
excessively; <as>as, to <ex>overwork</ex> a horse</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fill too full of work; to crowd with
labor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My days with toil are <qex>overwrought</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To decorate all over.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overwork</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Overwork
<hw>O`ver*work"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To work too much, or beyond
one's strength.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overwork</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Overwork
<hw>O"ver*work`</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Work in excess of the usual or
stipulated time or quantity; extra work; also, excessive
labor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overworn</ent>⟦br⟧
